Lab 11: Hyperparameter Tuning & Automated Machine Learning (AutoML)
Overview
This lab focuses on model optimization. While previous labs focused on building initial models, this lab explores the science of "tuning" them for peak performance. I implemented strategies to find the perfect settings (hyperparameters) for an algorithm and experimented with AutoML to see how AI can be used to build better AI.

Key Learning Objectives
Hyperparameters vs. Parameters: Learned the distinction between what a model learns (parameters) and the settings we define before training (hyperparameters), such as the depth of a tree or the number of estimators in a forest.

Optimization Strategies: Practiced two major tuning methods:

Grid Search: An exhaustive search through a manually specified subset of the hyperparameter space.

Random Search: A more efficient approach that samples configurations at random, often finding high-performing settings faster than Grid Search.

AutoML (AutoGluon): Introduced to Automated Machine Learning, where a system automatically handles data preprocessing, model selection, and hyperparameter optimization in a "leaderboard" format.

Tools & Libraries
Scikit-Learn: Used for GridSearchCV and RandomizedSearchCV.

AutoGluon: Used to demonstrate the power of TabularPredictors in an AutoML workflow.

Challenges & Insights
The Computational Trade-off: I discovered that Grid Search is powerful but "expensive" in terms of time and processing power. Random Search taught me that sometimes a "good enough" sample is more practical for real-world engineering than trying every single possibility.

The "Black Box" of AutoML: While AutoML (like AutoGluon) is incredibly fast and often more accurate than manual tuning, I realized the importance of the human "Ranger" in the loop to interpret the results and ensure the final model is grounded in reality.

"Ranger" Connection
In my Microscope Buddy project, tuning is the difference between a robot that "works" and a robot that is "precise." If the hyperparameters for my object detection model aren't tuned, the robot might be too slow or too sensitive. By understanding AutoML, I can potentially allow my robotics platform to self-calibrate, finding the best model settings automatically based on the specific lighting or sample type it encounters in the field.
